 and a refined sense of touch, the Osteopath is able to sense and cooperate with the intention of these forces to promote healing in the patient','Biodynamic Osteopathy','','inherit','open','open','','229-revision-3','','','2009-10-17 20:23:06','2009-10-17 10:23:06','',229,'http://www.dynamicbodytherapy.com/uncategorized/229-revision-3',0,'revision','',0),(242,1,'2009-10-17 17:39:06','2009-10-17 07:39:06','<h3><strong>What is osteopathy? </strong></h3>\r\nOsteopathy is a holistic based treatment using the hands to correct tissue &amp; joint abnormalities. It is aimed at restoring physical &amp; mental wellbeing and thereby making it easier for the body to use its own recuperative powers to heal itself. The treatment goal is to improve circulation, reduce muscle spasm, improve flexibility, maintain nerve supply &amp; restore muscle/joint harmony\r\n<h3><strong>What kinds of problems can osteopathy help with? </strong></h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Lower back pain, neck pain, &amp; other joint complaints</li>\r\n	<li>Headaches and migraines</li>\r\n	<li>Arthritic conditions</li>\r\n	<li>Sporting injuries such as tendonitis and strains, and stress-related muscle pain</li>\r\n	<li>Pregnancy-care for a great pregnancy and labour preparation</li>\r\n	<li>Treatment of babies and children</li>\r\n	<li>Digestive complaints such as reflux, constipation, IBS</li>\r\n	<li>Asthma and other breathing difficulties</li>\r\n	<li>And many more</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3><strong>How does osteopathy work? </strong></h3>\r\n<h4>Manipulative Osteopathy</h4>\r\nIs a â€˜whole bodyâ€™ system of manual medicine, based on unique biomechanical principles. The osteopath uses a wide range of techniques such as\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Massage and stretching techniques</li>\r\n	<li>Articulation techniques, in which joints are mobilised by being passively taken through their range of motion</li>\r\n	<li>Muscle Energy techniques, in which contracted muscles are released by alternately being stretched and made to work against resistance.</li>\r\n	<li>Positional Release Techniques, which achieve release of restriction by placing the affected joint or muscle in a position of comfort, while applying a stretching release to the opposing muscles.</li>\r\n	<li>Functional techniques, which involve gentle mobilisation of joints in a way which \"nudges\" barriers to normal movement until a way is found through the restriction</li>\r\n	<li>Manipulation, which may be used where it is appropriate and safe to do so, though it is not the mainstay of most Osteopathic treatments. Osteopathic manipulations are carried out using minimum force levels in order to maximise safety and minimise patient discomfort</li>\r\n	<li>Visceral techniques are used in the management of conditions affecting internal organs. These involve gentle and rhythmical stretching of the visceral areas</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h4><strong>Biodynamic Osteopathy</strong></h4>\r\nBiodynamic osteopaths are trained to feel a very subtle, rhythmical change that is present in all body tissues. Known as primary respiratory motion, this intuitive force is capable of restoring health in the patient. Through disciplined study and a refined sense of touch, the Osteopath is able to sense and cooperate with the intention of these forces to promote healing in the patient.<a href=\"/services/biodynamic-cranial-osteopathy\"> read more</a>\r\n<h3><strong>What can I expect when I visit an osteopath? </strong></h3>\r\nWhen you visit an osteopath for the first time a full case history will be taken and you will be taken through a physical examination. You will normally be asked to remove some of your clothing and to perform a simple series of movements. The osteopath will then use a highly developed sense of touch to identify any areas of tension, weakness or altered movement throughout the body.\r\n\r\nThe osteopath may need to request additional investigations such as x-ray or blood tests. This will allow a full diagnosis and suitable treatment plan to be developed for you.\r\n<h3><strong>Can I have osteopathy on my private medical insurance or Medicare? </strong></h3>\r\nMany private health insurance schemes give benefit for osteopathic treatment. Some companies will reimburse the total fee or pay a percentage of the costs. Contact your insurance company who will explain the actual benefits and methods of claim for your individual policy. Our clinic has HICAPS which allows for claims to be made on the spot.\r\n\r\nIf you are claiming your treatment on Medicare as part of an Extended Primary Care (EPC) scheme you must have the relevant documentation from your GP prior to your first visit.\r\n\r\nStaff:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a title=\"Shari Trimble\" href=\"/practitioners/shari\">Dr Shari Trimble</a></li>\r\n</ul>','Osteopathy','','inherit','open','open','','7-revision-19','','','2009-10-17 17:39:06','2009-10-17 07:39:06','',7,'http://www.dynamicbodytherapy.com/uncategorized/7-revision-19',0,'revision','',0),(243,1,'2009-10-17 18:12:10','2009-10-17 08:12:10','<img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-166\" src=\"http://www.dynamicbodytherapy.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/09/cranial-girl.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"170\" height=\"220\" />Biodynamic Osteopathy is a gentle approach to Osteopathic principles and the patient, which places particular emphasis on the spirit, health, and intelligence that is experienced when the patient is understood and perceived as a whole. Biodynamic osteopaths are trained to feel a very subtle, rhythmical change that is present in all body tissues. Known as primary respiratory motion, this intuitive force is capable of restoring health in the patient. Through disciplined study and a refined sense of touch, the Osteopath is able to sense and cooperate with the intention of these forces to promote healing in the patient.\r\n\r\nTo treat the practitioner gently places their hands on your body and adds to their traditional postural assessment an assessment of the whole being using the inner life rhythms as a diagnostic tool.Â  This enables the practitioner to assess the inner health and function of all organs and tissues of the body and also to gain an understanding of how other levels of being (energetic, emotional, mental and spiritual) are influencing the health and wellbeing of the individual assessed.\r\n\r\nTogether with traditional methods of treatment such as manipulation, articulation and soft tissue therapy (which can still be used where appropriate), biodynamic Osteopathy helps to enhance long term health in patients with a wider variety of health issues.\r\n\r\nFor more information on this type of therapy, please call and speak to one of our Osteopaths.','Biodynamic/Cranial Osteopathy','','inherit','open','open','','28-revision-10','','','2009-10-17 18:12:10','2009-10-17 08:12:10','',28,'http://www.dynamicbodytherapy.com/uncategorized/28-revision-10',0,'revision','',0),(244,1,'2009-10-17 17:53:07','2009-10-17 07:53:07','[caption id=\"attachment_103\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"256\" caption=\"Dr Shari Trimble\"]<img class=\"size-full wp-image-103\" title=\"Dr Shari Trimble\" src=\"http://www.dynamicbodytherapy.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/10/shari.jpg\" alt=\"Dr Shari Trimble\" width=\"256\" height=\"329\" />[/caption]\r\n\r\nDr Shari Trimble\r\nOsteopath, Prescriptive Exercise Consultant\r\nM.H.Sc. [Osteo], B.Sc [Clin], M.C.O.C.A\r\n\r\nMONDAY 1pm - 7pm\r\nWEDNESDAY 1pm - 7pm\r\nFRIDAY 3:15pm - 6:30pm\r\n\r\nShari is the co owner of the practice with Camille de Niese. She has worked in the health and manual medicine field for more than 15 years and also lectures in anatomy, pathology and clinical skills.\r\n\r\nShariâ€™s passion is to assist in helping the body\'s own wisdom restore health and balance. With a nurturing and gentle style, Shari tailors her treatments to each individual, working to stimulate the body\'s natural ability to heal itself.\r\n\r\n<strong>Special Interest in Yoga and Performance Arts</strong>\r\n\r\nWith her past experience in engineering, a Bachelor degree in Clinical Science and a Masters in Osteopathy, Shari has a thorough understanding of body mechanics and a unique capacity to view your injury in the context of activity and training. Shari focuses on helping you to rehabilitate your injury whilst continuing to practice and train, and how to avoid further disruption to your program.\r\n\r\nCurrently a member of the Footscray Womenâ€™s Circus Shari also runs her dogs and practices yoga daily. She has a background in dance, pilates and long distance running and has completed postgraduate studies in exercise prescription &amp; clinical pilates.\r\n\r\n<strong>Special Interests in Womenâ€™s Health, Fertility &amp; Children</strong>\r\n\r\nShari has completed post graduate osteopathic studies in obstetrics &amp; gynaecology and the treatment of children and enjoys working with the challenges women may face during pregnancy and motherhood.\r\n\r\n<strong>Pregnancy</strong>\r\n\r\nDuring pregnancy there are many physiological processes that take place and large changes to a womenâ€™s body occur in a relatively short space of time. A hormone called Relaxin softens the ligaments around the joints of the pelvis which is a natural process and assists childbirth. However for some women this process can cause the joints of the pelvis to loosen too much and can result in the pelvis becoming unstable or out of alignment and in a susceptible women can contribute to low back and pelvic pain.\r\n\r\nPost pregnancy there will be pressure on different areas such as the upper back and neck. This may be due to poor posture during breast feeding and incorrect lifting techniques.Â  Osteopathic treatment and corrective muscle re-education can aid in the way the body copes with these pressures.\r\n\r\n<strong>Babies &amp; Children</strong>\r\n\r\nA baby will often communicate there is a problem by being unsettled, irritable or wakeful. Symptoms in a newborn baby to be aware of are:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Colic</li